This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new algorithm for imitation learning that combines distribution matching and reinforcement learning. It also introduces a new objective function that is off-policy, which is a common topic in machine learning research. Additionally, the paper evaluates the proposed algorithm on popular imitation learning benchmarks, which is a common practice in machine learning research. 

The paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as imitation learning is a subfield of AI that focuses on learning from expert demonstrations. 

Furthermore, the paper could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.RO (Robotics) as imitation learning is commonly used in robotics to teach robots how to perform tasks. 

The paper could also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) as imitation learning is often used in computer vision applications such as object recognition and tracking. 

Finally, the paper could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.SY (Systems and Control) as imitation learning is used in control systems to learn how to control a system based on expert demonstrations.
